name: Hassaku XL (Illustrious)
description:
Hassaku aims to be a anime model with a bright and distinct anime style.

You can run Hassaku XL and use its API on SinkIn: https://sinkin.ai/m/JWknjgr

My Discord for everything related to anime models and art.
You can support me on my patreon.

____________________________________________________________
Supporters:

Thanks to my supporters Riyu, SETI and Kodokuna on my patreon!

____________________________________________________________
Using the model:

  • The model is trained using images with minimal disruptive elements such as floating text, logos, speech bubbles, and signatures. If any of these elements are present in an image, please include the prompt "signature" as a negative prompt

  • Metadata and franchise tags are excludedâ€”please do not use them. Tags such as "highres" and franchise-related tags like "re:zero kara hajimeru isekai seikatsu" are not used in training

  • Look at the example images, to see how the model should be used

  • Model is trained to be not complicated in use, tag order:
    First are the number of person, then character names, rest.
    Example: 1girl, rem \(re:zero\), standing, masterpiece, upper body

  • Here are some resolution options for SDXL:

    • 1536 x 640

    • 1344 x 768

    • 1216 x 832

    • 1152 x 896

    • 1024 x 1024

    • 896 x 1152

    • 832 x 1216 (most recommended)

    • 768 x 1344

    • 640 x 1536


______________________________________________________

Version and License info:

  • Below V1 merges ANIMAGINE XL 3.0

  • Version V1 use Illustrious-XL & WAI-NSFW-illustrious-SDXL with additional training

  • V2 is trained on its own and don't include any extra merge. Base was V1, it is trained to include newer or missing characters. It was also used for further training tests

  • V3 is a merge of Illustrious-XL and V2, to fix some issues and was also trained to include newer or missing characters

    All Models using the Fair AI Public License 1.0-SD license.

modelVersions.name: v3.0
modelVersions.description:
Be aware that this is a WIP model, WIP means the knowleghe of new characters, outsite of that, it is a full working model.

The model occasionally performs better when using more than 75 tokens, that will change in a later update.

Model is training on changing datasets, ranging from 120k to around 760k images. The primary learning dataset (70k images) included characters from the past year (01.06.2024 of last year to now), with at least 100 images on Danbooru. The learning dataset was heavily filtered by score and quality, compressing it to a relative small size of 70k images. Note: While the most recent characters from the last week are included, they are not yet trained well enough to be reliable (like Sameko Saba).

In Detail:
Over the past two months, I ran into several issues. After about two weeks of training, the model began to deteriorate rapidly for no apparent reason.

As a result, I had to do one hard reset and two soft resets during the process, effectively throwing away a lot of time, effort, and money. I only discovered the root cause at the beginning of this month. So, this current version is still mid-training. It mainly includes faces and hairstyles of new characters, while clothing is still in the process to get learned for the most part. I'm sharing it now despite the state it's in, as I'm already 2 months over my schedule now.

This model has a style merge, which can sometimes lead to artifacts on the eyes, especially viewed from a distance. This aligns what other models are doing.

modelVersions.name: v2.2
modelVersions.description:
Model was trained on more actual data, but only on a small dataset of 50k images (mostly mihoyo games). With a month of experimenting and a hard reset inbetween, because of better training settings. New characters are relative weak trained in and the style merge mostly erased details of them, in which mostly the clothing suffers. It is more or less a prototype to not make the same mistakes of V2.1, that resulted in sampler problems.

better (all in compare to 2.1fix)
- Less orange looking images
- Style is overall more even torwards anime
- Model is a bit less restrictive and more expressive

worse for some
- more anime looking, which also makes backgrounds less detailed and less cohesive
- less mature looking faces
- Can be darker on some concepts (also more shadows on faces)
- Pupils are more filled out (less circle pupils)

worse
- hands/fingers
- text (model goes more towards japanese writing, when it wants to generate text, which is disjointed)

Can't say
- Loras should work better, because of a better inner style merge, with much less artifacts. But i can see that a strong style can backup loras to work better. It mostly depends of the loras itself.

2.1fix have a more 2.5d feel to it, like more details on bodys (like showing rips more often). Which also translate to backgrounds. If you like that, you can still use 2.1fix further.
If you question why i can't stay on the same qualitys of 2.1fix, its because i can't be more "reckless" in my mergin, without actual hurting the new knowledge in the model. Mergin another model in, erase every training I done on it, because all other models knowing less then my model. While every longer training on it, resets it to be like every other base model like noob or illustriuos, without style merge.

modelVersions.name: v2.1fix
modelVersions.description:
Because my 2.2 Version needs a bit more time then expected. I made this fixed version of 2.1. Issues of this version was a to high style merge overall, resulting in unexpected issues with samplers and unwanted side effects.

I reduced the style merge significatly and merged style A in, because style A is overall more liked. Not only because its more stable, but also for its simpler but still detailed style.

2.1fix should have a lot less issues sampler side and resembles style A more or less in some aspects. Drawback of mergin A back is, that newer characters are getting erased in this fixed version. But that seems for most not that big of a problem, especially with the use of loras.

Note: Fixed Style is weaker on the fix version, the variety of different styles that can appear is much higher. If you don't like that faces can appear more realistic, put nose into the negatives.

modelVersions.name: v2.1
modelVersions.description:
Only a performance update, no new characters or such.


Improvements:
- Better-formed eyes
- Better hands
- Fewer artifacts overall

Worse:
- Backgrounds can look more blurry, noisy or messy, describing the background a bit more can change that
- It makes sometimes strange dark orange like images

Recommended negatives are "worst quality, bad quality, sketch". With negative "sketch" giving more clean line art (most of the time). Sometimes not using worst quality, bad quality, gives better results, strangely enough.

Style A tends to produce better eyes with a more stable style overall, while Style 2.1 offers more detailed images with a less 2D appearance. If you prefer images with added detail and depth, Style 2.1 might be the better choice for you. Even if you need to kick the model in the balls sometimes.

Note: Some concepts have a strong drawn appearence and others more of a 2.5 feel (especially with character prompts, giving more drawn results). The price of more versatility in general. Don't overload it with quality prompts or a wall of text prompts, its versatility is also its weakness. Overloading it with too much information can cause the model to produce unhinged results, because it don't have a strong "style saveguard".


In maybe 2-3 weeks i have a dataset updated model, but it only offers new genshin characters so far.

modelVersions.name: v2
modelVersions.description:
It behaves and looks mostly like Style A, less flat looking but also more drawn in a way. Model style is now build up from the ground up, without any other merge, like mergin with wai, simply to actualy update my model on new concepts. Because of that, its basicly a new model and a bit less stable in compare to style A.

Don't expect, because its named V2, thats magicaly much better. When you train, merge or make any changes, it tends to impact other concepts significantly. V2 means a new base to work on.

Compared to 1.3 A, a honest review over my own model:

Improvements:
- Better at prompt following
- Clearer images with less of a "fog" over the image (for concepts that had that)
- Slightly better at handling furry-related prompts
- For most concepts, more filled and coherent backgrounds
- Better at artist tags

Improvements for some:
- Model have a bit more freedom and variety, that comes also with a wider array of style on a singe concept (some images are more detailed and others are more flat on the same prompt)
- Stronger contrast, but some concepts have a yellow tint
- Bodys have more details, with less 2d flatness, featuring a slight shine and sometimes stronger outlines
- Faces appear slightly more mature
- It likes to draw fingernails more often

Worse:
- Nights are less dark
- Some images can look overexposed or "burnt" on color
- Bodys, because they are more detailed, can look washed out, at some prompt combinations
- Artifacts are more frequent; slightly worse than style A, but much better in compare to style B
- Eyes forming less well-formed pupils (dependent on concept and character distance), in combi with more artifacts, makes it harder to have clear eyes. A point to use Style A over V2. But it also have a bit to do, that faces are more mature looking and having smaller eyes with it.
- Looks sometimes "dirty"
- A bit more unstable

The model was further trained on an dataset of around 60k (more recent characters) to 600k (total images).

Will work first on a update, to make eyes, lines and overall look more clear and harmonic

modelVersions.name: v1.3 - Style A
modelVersions.description:
Whats better:
- Images are overall a bit more brighter

Worse/better for some:
- It is more forced to look more "anime" and less realistic -> mostly less images with visible nostrils/noses without tags like realistic or detailed, especially in use of tags censored/uncensored

Worse:
- Artifacts can appear more
- Because of the second point (looks more "anime"), images getting less of a "cinematic" look with lighting

It is recommended, if you want to use loras, to use it on the style A variant model. Forced Style is light enough, that most artist tags still works and loras can do their thing, including pony loras.

modelVersions.name: v1.3 - Style B
modelVersions.description: A model purely to have a interesting style, it have many flaws, including artifacts (especially eyes) and composition problems. But using highres or Adetailer can avoid that flows (or using a sampler with less artifact susceptibility). If model variant B turns out to be popular, i will maybe work on this model further.

modelVersions.name: v1.2 - Style
modelVersions.description:
Model 1.2 without early access as christmas gift! examples are now with highress fix.
V1.2 my attempt to reduce eye and image artifacts


Whats better:
- Eye and image artifacts reduced
- More stable in image composition
- Some concepts having a clearer image output

Focusing on making backgrounds better next, without getting artifacts back, especially on the eyes.

Edit: After people tested it, it seems artifacts got worse on specific promts, but got overall better. Working on that also. The new version is a bit more prompt following in compare to the last version, so its more important to use the right negative promt "bad quality" instead of "low quality".

modelVersions.name: v1.1 - Style
modelVersions.description:
V1.1 The Style variant with a bit more training under the hood, but overall not a big update.

Because of additional training that can be used for a stronger merge, some problems are fixed:

- Removed the noise, that is sometimes noticable to a minimal level
- Faces and bodys are less different in style

Whats better:

- Backgrounds are a bit better constructed
- Things that are not normaly in anime models present, working better
- Poses are a little bit more stable
- Blacks are more black, especially on dark backgrounds (also because of the reduced noise)

Worse/better for some:

- Backgrounds are less realistic but more in a drawn style (losing details basicly, but fits better a anime character in front)
- Some themes have a "softer" style to them

What remained and got a bit worse:
- Eye errors/artifacts can appear, eye problems are stronger

modelVersions.name: V1.0 - Style
modelVersions.description:
V1 - Style Variant got a "soft" treatment of my hassaku pony V1.3 model .

The Style is more forced to a less basic 2d look and got enhancements in backgrounds, structure and details.

Because of that, artist tags and details on clothes of characters are less precise, especially for more complex clothing or lesser known characters. Faces of characters on the other hand should work fine, for the most part.

If you want to use artist tags or want it to look more "drawn" and less "AI generated", use the normal V1 Version.

Short: It now have a style merge, but not that much, to left freedom in the model. Also to prevent burned/artifact images, resulting in clean and smooth images.

I recommend to use clip 1 and not 2 (civit generator use clip 2), to have added extra details.

Notes:

  • There is sometimes some noise noticeble, because of heavy merging for better backgrounds. I fix that later (if possible, without losing to much of he backgrounds)

  • Eye errors/artifacts can appear, especially from far or if no eye color is prompted

  • Bodys can appear more detailed in compare to the faces, especially with characters. Thats a side effect of the forced less basic 2d style.

modelVersions.name: V1.0
modelVersions.description:
This model was trained on more up-to-date data, it can be considered between Illustrius and NoobAI-XL in terms of its look.

It don't have a strong style merge, like Wai or NTR, to have stronger responding artist tags.

The base model is Illustrious-XL, trained on a dataset ranging from 70k to 440k images (to update Illustrious-XL), primarily making sure that newer Genshin characters, ZZZ and Wuthering Waves characters are trained in.

It was later merged with WAI-NSFW-illustrious-SDXL, to achieve a more consistent style, but it loses a bit of my character training, like details on clothes (and loses appearence of characters with lower image counts).

If you want 1to1 clothes like of newer characters from ZZZ, the clothes are mostly off and wrong in detail, i will fix that in the next version.

modelVersions.name: beta V0.6
modelVersions.description:
Probably the last update of my sdxl model, it simply proven to hard to train on a single 4090. Trained on 1.2mio images for 2epochs. I maybe need 3-4 more months to make it even with pony in nsfw capabilitys. Sadly that time is not there anymore. But my model is in other aspects also good (at least better at nsfw then animagine).

Waiting and preparing for SD3 now.

modelVersions.name: beta V0.4
modelVersions.description:
Version v0.4 is right, decided to upload my current training state up, instead to put it up on my patreon, skipping my 0.3 model. Trained on 650k questionable and explizit images, as result, it is much more lewd then before and shows breast much more willingly (sometimes a bit to much). Adding now much much more sfw images into my dataset.

Goal was to make nsfw more stable with better formed out details. Image composition doesn't changed much, but the model is overall much more responsive to artist tags and better at some character likeness.

Animagine (my compare model for now), is in my oppinion better at sfw works and does make more details at some prompts. Want to make it even in capabilities.

modelVersions.name: beta V0.2M
modelVersions.description:
A version that implements Animagine into HassakuXL in a way that cancels eachother weaknesses out.

- Animagine gives much needed style coherency to hassaku
- hassaku gives much more nsfw stability, bit better lighting and plasticity

But masterpiece, best quality in positiv and worst quality, low quality, normal quality, signature, blurry, in negative are mandatory. With additional nsfw in negative, if you want more precise sfw art.

modelVersions.name: beta V0.2
modelVersions.description: Be aware on 0.2: Sometimes some concepts on some resolutions looking really basic and flat. Model remains propably long as beta version. Concentrate now mostly to improve capability to promt certain characters. My model can do genshin and blue archive characters at some extend, but have a hard time on others.

modelVersions.name: beta V0.1
modelVersions.description:
first beta version of my sdxl model.

Was planning to have artist tag recognition and some extra conzepts, but again, sdxl fighting me here and getting me actually a bit into my nerves.

It is simply a bit more stable in its general style.

modelVersions.name: alpha V0.9
modelVersions.description:
V9: Images have a slightly blurry effect and some concept have strong tendencies to create really basic 2d images now. It is sometimes a bit of a gamble between basic 2d images and more detailed ones.

Blurry because i trained some days on the edge of possibility, to make it more anime now. More basic images are in a learning transition, those images simply doesn't looks great, because of it.

modelVersions.name: alpha V0.7
modelVersions.description:
Eyes having a bit more problems, nsfw got a bit more precise.

Bodys have a bit less wingles and stuff, albeit only a little less for te most part.

I noticed that anything in negative goes sometimes a bit crazy, with a drop of quality. Not sure how to change that.

It sadly don't learn faster, changes are not that big inbetween versions.

Concentrating a bit more on sfw now, without negleting nsfw.

modelVersions.name: alpha V0.5
modelVersions.description: unfortunately it doesnâ€™t make that much progress overall and hands are bad. SDXL is fighting me here. Tested also some block and general merges for stabilisation. But even minimal merges results in damaging anything nsfw highly, because no other sdxl model cames close in nsfw capabilities to mine (so far i know). Without a RL sdxl model in the same lewdness liga like basilMix (chilloutMix), prevents me to correct things like degrading backgrounds (because most images in training feature only simple backgrounds). Hoped to get it more 2d like, i achieve it in some cases, but the big majority remains mostly more realistic.

modelVersions.name: alpha V0.4
modelVersions.description: it remains unstable and have a bug with prompt ":3", on some promts, its making a transition from 2.5d to 2d or is in a mid state to a new trained in image. Looks overall weid sometimes, like strange big shadows instead of lines. Tested it a bit more and i need to work on some dataset imbalances. Next update is not in a week but in 1,5-2 weeks.

modelVersions.name: alpha V0.3
modelVersions.description: Because of some selective training, it seems that it got a bit unstable, especially hands have more problems. I'm not satisfied with the result, but it is overall slittly better then before.

modelVersions.name: alpha V0.2
modelVersions.description:
It is simply a continuation of training with a extended dataset.

With many diffent styles, eyes getting a bit unprecise, testing it only for training check. I can fix that, but i spend that time better on further training and dataset working, instead staying and spending time on a between Version.
